module ast
  source: ["ast.go","expr.go"]
  why: "AST node types for the Lyric syntax parser: positions, spans, declarations, statements, expressions, and type expressions. The two source files divide declarations/statements (ast.go) from expressions (expr.go)."

  doc "Architecture":
    """
    The ast module defines the Abstract Syntax Tree for the Forge/Lyric
    language. It is a passive, data-oriented package: it defines the schema for
    the compiler's intermediate representation but contains no processing logic.
    The same node types represent both .lyric (declaration-only) and .fg (full
    code) source files.

    The tree is organized hierarchically. A File is the root node for one source
    file; it holds a list of LyricBlocks plus all source comments. A LyricBlock
    is a named container (e.g. module ast { ... }) that interleaves imports,
    narrative docs, invariants, and declarations. Declarations (ClassDecl,
    StructDecl, EnumDecl, InterfaceDecl, FuncDecl, RelationDecl, ImplBlock,
    ConstDecl, TypeAliasDecl) define the program's structure and API.
    Statements and Expressions, found inside function bodies and initializers,
    represent executable logic.

    Rather than deep interface hierarchies, variant node families use a flat
    "Kind + Data" pattern: a Kind enum discriminates the node while a Data field
    of type any holds the kind-specific struct. This applies uniformly to
    TypeExpr, Expr, Stmt, and Pattern, simplifying traversal (Go type switches)
    and serialization at the cost of some compile-time type safety.

    The AST is the medium of exchange across compiler stages: the parser
    constructs nodes and fills Span data; the checker resolves names and
    populates the any-typed ResolvedType and InferredTypeArgs fields; desugaring
    passes may inject fields or destructors; and codegen performs a final
    traversal to emit target code.
    """

  doc "Dependencies":
    """
    The ast module is intentionally at the bottom of the dependency graph. It
    imports only the Go standard library (fmt) and no other pkg/ modules. This
    prevents circular dependencies, since almost every other compiler module
    (parser, checker, codegen) needs to import ast.
    """

  doc "Design Decisions":
    """
    Checker-populated fields (Expr.ResolvedType, Pattern.ResolvedType,
    CallExpr.InferredTypeArgs) are typed as any rather than *checker.Type. This
    deliberately avoids an import cycle between ast and checker: ast stays
    dependency-free and the checker stores its concrete types behind the any.

    Declaration bodies are optional. FuncDecl.Body is a *Block that is nil for
    .lyric declaration-only files and populated for .fg full-code files, letting
    one node type serve both parsing modes.

    Relations and interface fields enable Forge's automated data modeling.
    RelationDecl (owns/refs) together with InterfaceFieldDecl and
    DestructorBlock allow fields and destructor code declared on an interface to
    be injected into concrete classes during desugaring, supporting structures
    like doubly-linked lists and parent-child hierarchies.
    """

  invariant "Kind + Data variant pattern":
    procedural
    """
    Every variant node family — TypeExpr, Expr, Stmt, and Pattern — is
    represented as a Kind enum tag plus a Data field of type any. The dynamic
    type stored in Data must correspond to the value of Kind (e.g. an Expr with
    Kind == ExprCall carries a CallExpr in Data; a TypeExpr with Kind ==
    TypeMap carries a MapType). Consumers switch on Kind and type-assert Data
    accordingly. This pattern is applied consistently across all four families
    and is the module's central structural invariant.
    """

  invariant "AST is a passive data-definition package":
    procedural
    """
    The ast module defines only data structures and their trivial accessors
    (such as File.DocComment and the Kind String() methods). It contains no
    parsing, type-checking, transformation, or code-generation logic. All
    processing lives in other packages that consume these types.
    """

  invariant "No internal module dependencies":
    procedural
    """
    The ast module depends only on the Go standard library (fmt) and must never
    import another pkg/ module. Because almost every compiler module imports
    ast, any such dependency would create an import cycle.
    """

  invariant "Checker-populated fields are opaque any":
    procedural
    """
    Expr.ResolvedType, Pattern.ResolvedType, and CallExpr.InferredTypeArgs are
    typed as any (holding *checker.Type / []*checker.Type). They are empty when
    the parser produces a node and are filled in later by the checker. ast must
    not reference checker types directly, so these fields stay any to avoid an
    import cycle.
    """

  invariant "Function bodies are present only in full-code files":
    procedural
    """
    FuncDecl.Body is a *Block that is nil for declaration-only (.lyric) files
    and non-nil for full-code (.fg) files. The same node type serves both
    parsing modes; consumers must treat a nil Body as "declaration only".
    """

  invariant "String interpolation parts alternate literal and expression":
    procedural
    """
    StringInterpExpr.Parts alternates between string-literal parts
    (ExprStringLit) and arbitrary interpolated expressions. The slice always
    starts and ends with a string literal (which may be empty), so literal and
    interpolated parts strictly interleave.
    """

  struct Annotations
    source: ast.go:144
    why: "Annotations holds all function/method annotations."
    field Why: string
    field Concurrent: *bool
      doc: "nil = not specified"
    field RequiresLock: []string
    field ExcludesLock: []string
    field Raises: []string
    field Requires: []string
      doc: "preconditions"
    field Ensures: []string
      doc: "postconditions"
    field Spawns: bool
    field Pure: bool

  struct AssignStmt
    source: expr.go:321
    why: "AssignStmt assigns a value to a target (ident, field access, or index)."
